  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nGovernments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering due to its association with criminal activity and its potential to undermine the integrity of financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, imprisonment, and seizure of assets. \n\nKey international efforts to combat money laundering include the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards, and various national laws, such as the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** in the United States, the **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** in the UK, and the **Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act (AML/CTF Act)** in Australia.",
